    <node id="1. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers play a significant role in ensuring schools effectively use and demonstrate the impact of their PDG resources for school improvement work by scrutinizing how schools utilize these funds and asking probing questions about their strategies, impact, and outcomes. This helps maintain a focus on ensuring that PDG resources are used to their full potential and contribute to improved educational opportunities and outcomes for disadvantaged learners.&#10;2. By challenging and supporting schools in using PDG funds, regional consortia can help raise awareness of the availability and importance of these resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This approach promotes more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and helps narrow the attainment gap.&#10;3. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers are crucial in fostering a regional approach to good practice, as they can facilitate collaboration and knowledge-sharing among schools to identify successful strategies for utilizing PDG funds effectively. This helps create a culture of continuous improvement and ensures that best practices are disseminated and adopted more widely.&#10;4. To maximize the impact of regional consortia's challenge and support advisers in this area, it is essential to provide them with adequate training, resources, and guidance on PDG policies and best practices. Strengthening their role and capacities will enable them to contribute more effectively to school improvement efforts and help ensure that PDG funds are used in ways that lead to better outcomes for disadvantaged learners." />
    <node id=" about, the expertise—how we can keep that expertise in the system, and how we can apply the lessons to all schools.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: The next questions, and the final questions, are from John. So, we're going to need succinct questions and succinct answers.&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths AM&#10;Content: Some questions on regional consortia, Cabinet Secretary, and, first of all, the role that you believe they should play and how schools use PDG.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, it's an absolute—. It's one of the things that I have been very clear to the regional consortia that I expect their challenge and support advisers to be asking schools about. So, one of the conversations that they need to have when they are in schools is exploring, with that school, how they are using their PDG, and how they're demonstrating an impact for those resources. So, it's a fundamental role for the challenge and support advisers in the regional consortia in their school improvement work. It's crucial.&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths AM&#10;Content: That sort of brings to mind some of the research that's been done" />
    <node id="1. Acknowledgement of Research Findings: Kirsty Williams AM acknowledges the research findings that challenge advisers are not effectively challenging schools to change their use of PDG, which is why she has taken steps to address this issue.&#10;2. Appointment of New Regional PDG Advisers: To improve the effectiveness of PDG usage, new regional PDG advisers have been appointed with the aim of spreading good practice across regions and ensuring strategic and consistent use of PDG in all schools. These advisers will provide overall advice on effective deployment of PDG funds.&#10;3. Strengthening the Role of Regional Challenge Advisers: By working closely with individual schools, regional challenge advisers will be challenged to examine their use of PDG, including how it is targeted and spent, and whether there is an evidence base for its use and a clear impact on student learning.&#10;4. Promoting Good Practice Regionally: Regional advisers will ensure that school challenge advisers are aware of best practices in using PDG, especially in targeting and spending decisions, encouraging schools to adopt these strategies to maximize the effectiveness of PDG funds.&#10;5. Encouraging Early Intervention: Regional advisers will emphasize the importance of early intervention strategies, using PDG funds earlier in a child's career rather than just before exams, to provide support and address learning needs proactively.&#10;6. Monitoring and Demonstrating Proper Use of PDG: Regional advisers will ensure that measures are in place to demonstrate that PDG is being used appropriately and consistently across schools, assessing the impact of PDG spending on student outcomes and making adjustments as needed." />
