    <node id="1. The transcript does not provide specific information on why the money from the Schools Challenge Cymru program was returned to reserves instead of staying in the education budget. Kirsty Williams AM mentioned that it was a time-limited program and they secured investment from the Finance Minister to run it. However, the decision to return the funds to reserves is not explained in the transcript.&#10;2. It is also important to note that the Schools Challenge Cymru program was explicitly designed to run for a specific period, although the exact duration is not provided in the transcript. The transcript does mention that there are ongoing discussions with the Minister for Finance around support for the education budget.&#10;3. In summary, while the transcript provides context about the time-limited nature of the Schools Challenge Cymru program and the government's commitment to school improvement, it does not explicitly address the question of why the funds were returned to reserves instead of being kept in the education budget." />
    <node id=" programme. That's not to say it was the wrong decision, because what's important, and an ongoing legacy of the programme, was the investment in regional school improvement capacity, because at the time our school improvement services and the regions were young, in their infancy. The ability of individual local authorities to make a difference, with so many local authorities in an Estyn categorisation, was limited, so one of the ongoing legacies of the programme is that significant investment of over £10 million in the capacity of the regions to be able to continue this support and the school improvement work.&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffydd AM&#10;Content: So, how disappointed were you that the money for Schools Challenge Cymru went back into reserves and didn't stay in your envelope, as you described it earlier? I presume you made a pitch for it. Did you make a case for that money to stay within your department?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Llyr, we are constantly having discussions with the Minister for Finance around support for the education budget. The Minister for Finance was quite clear that it was a time-limited programme. We were able to secure investment from the Finance Minister to be able to secure the programme and run it" />
    <node id="1. The evolution of using the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG) in Welsh schools has not been significantly driven by cuts to core funding but rather by an increased focus on the agenda, improved understanding, and a better utilization of growing research and evidence.&#10;2. PDG funds have played a crucial role in concentrating the minds of school leadership and senior management teams, highlighting the importance of this agenda within schools and raising it in their thinking.&#10;3. As schools embark on a journey from a low base where this was not a priority for them, they are increasingly learning to use evidence and research from both Wales and outside sources to tailor approaches in their schools. This reflects the changing use of PDG funds.&#10;4. Regional consortia collaborate with schools to improve the use of PDG funds for looked-after children, although there is less awareness about PDG's availability due to fewer numbers and a historical focus on free school meals. Increased communication and understanding of PDG's role in supporting this vulnerable group are essential.&#10;5. The new schools categorization system targets resources towards schools with greater needs, regardless of their type or sector, incorporating well-being into the national mission and addressing various challenges faced by children within the school setting.&#10;6. Effective use of PDG funds includes leadership development, strategic usage, early intervention, and proper monitoring to ensure good practice is shared across regions and that PDG funds are not used to cover other funding gaps." />
    <node id=" You mentioned some schools will be moving from the tried-and-tested interventions, really, and I'm just wondering to what extent that evolution of use of PDG is being driven by cuts to core funding.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: No, I don't think it's being driven by cuts to core funding. I think there has been—. One of the biggest impacts of PDG has not been—well, I suppose it is the money in itself, because the money has concentrated the minds, hasn't it? So, one of the most important things that PDG has done is highlight the importance of this agenda within schools, and really raise this up in the thinking of leadership and senior management teams in our schools, and has driven a focus on scrutiny and accountability in the systems that are working with our schools. I think the changing use of PDG reflects the journeys that schools have been on, some of them from a very low base where this was not a priority for them, to better understanding, and as research and as intelligence grows over time in this area, both in Wales and outside of Wales, schools are increasingly learning to use that evidence to tailor approaches in their schools.&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffy" />
    <node id="1. Regarding the recruitment process and diversity in the Schools Challenge Cymru program, Professor Ainscow highlighted the success of the program in recruiting high-quality individuals from diverse backgrounds and experiences. He feels there is more to learn about how to support real excellence and diversity in recruitment for positions within the regional consortia. This insight suggests that he could provide valuable suggestions on improving recruitment and diversity based on his deep understanding of the Schools Challenge Cymru program and its successes.&#10;2. Cabinet Secretary Kirsty Williams is open to further conversations about lessons learned from the Schools Challenge Cymru program, but she also expresses confidence that they have already applied those lessons to the wider school improvement agenda. However, she acknowledges the value of ongoing dialogue with people involved in the program and considers developing a Welsh toolkit around good practice, evidence base, and research. Therefore, there is a possibility for Professor Ainscow to provide further input to the Welsh Government on this matter, especially if he has additional insights that can help improve recruitment and diversity within the regional consortia." />
    <node id="Based on the transcript, the lack of grade stability and resilience among children on free school meals is a complex issue that cannot be attributed solely to exam boards or the Welsh Qualifications Authority (WQA). Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, acknowledges that it could be one of the contributory factors but also mentions ongoing discussions with Qualifications Wales to better understand this. She has asked them to formally submit evidence ahead of her policy board meeting in May for a deeper investigation into this matter. It is clear that while exam boards and WQA are being considered as part of the problem, a broader examination of contributing factors and best practices is taking place." />
