    <node id="1. The growth mindset approach, implemented through the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG), has been shown to have a positive impact on the academic performance of free-school-meal children at the primary school level. This approach encourages learners to believe that they can improve their abilities and overcome failures, making them more resilient.&#10;2. Although this growth mindset training is provided universally to all students in a school, it has been observed to have a disproportionately positive effect on free-school-meal children. As a result, these children are now performing at the same level as their non-free-school-meal counterparts.&#10;3. This distinction is important because while individual interventions should be targeted specifically at children eligible for free school meals, whole-school approaches can also be effective in improving educational outcomes for this vulnerable group. By training all teachers and fostering a growth mindset ethos throughout the school, free-school-meal children benefit significantly.&#10;4. The key to successfully implementing the growth mindset approach through PDG funds is ensuring that schools use these resources effectively and demonstrate their impact on academic performance. Regional consortia play a crucial role in challenging and supporting schools in this process, promoting best practices and facilitating collaboration among educators." />
    <node id=" their results for free-school-meal children at the end of their primary school period in school are equivalent to their non-free-school-meal counterparts. So, there is no differentiation in those results. One of the things that they've used their PDG for is to really focus on the concept of growth mindset in school. So, that's a universal thing that they've trained all the teachers in, but what we know is that that has a disproportionate effect on those children who are on free school meals. So, if you're familiar with the concept of a growth mindset, it's about really challenging learners to think that, 'I can do things. If sometimes I fail, I pick myself up, I'm more resilient.' Now, that has been, as I said, trained to all the teachers in the school—it's an ethos for the whole school—but we have seen that the impact on the free-school-meal children has been even greater, and now they're at the same level. So, that's the important distinction. Individual intervention per child has to be targeted at those children who are eligible for free school meals, but sometimes a school will employ a whole-school approach to train their staff, for instance, and that," />
    <node id="1. The new schools categorization system in Wales provides a more targeted and intensive level of support for identified schools by using improvement boards to identify schools based on their level of need, with &quot;red&quot; schools entitled to 25 days of support. This is an increase from the 20 days of support provided under the Schools Challenge Cymru program. The new system targets resources towards schools with greater needs, regardless of their type or sector, which was not the case with the previous program that only supported secondary schools.&#10;2. This new system also addresses various challenges faced by children within the school setting, ensuring they receive the necessary support to remain in school. By incorporating well-being into the national mission, it ensures that schools identified as needing improvement will receive the required intensive support to help them make improvements. Examples of Schools Challenge Cymru schools have sustained progress even after the program has ended, indicating the potential for success with this new system.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is taking steps to improve the PDG (Pupil Development Grant) agenda at a regional level by appointing new regional PDG advisers. This will ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, promoting good practice regionally. This further strengthens the support provided to schools in need of improvement under the new system." />
    <node id="1. The recency of headteacher appointments and the effectiveness of support advisers played significant roles in the varying performance of schools in a program, as acknowledged by various speakers in the meeting transcript. Newly appointed headteachers were identified as contributing significantly to the speed at which schools engage with improvement efforts, as seen in a significant minority of schools with recent appointments. Additionally, the effectiveness of support advisers and challenge advisers varied, with some being &quot;really, really excellent and really good&quot; and driving change within individual schools, while others were less effective. The needs and challenges of individual schools also played a role in their performance, as some schools had more complex and deep-seated issues that required more intensive intervention." />
    <node id="1. Improved inter-agency collaboration: Strengthening the partnership between education, social services, and health is crucial for improving the educational attainment of looked-after children. This can be achieved by establishing a joined-up approach where all parties work together to address the complex needs of these children. Regular meetings and communication channels should be set up to discuss each child's progress and plan their support accordingly.&#10;&#10;2. Early intervention strategies: Local authorities can play a significant role in implementing early intervention strategies to identify and support looked-after children with additional learning needs (ALN) as soon as possible. This includes recognizing the connections between ALN and behavior issues that may lead to exclusion or non-attendance. By addressing these challenges proactively, local authorities can help prevent further deterioration in educational outcomes for these vulnerable children.&#10;&#10;3. Strategic use of PDG: Local authorities should ensure that schools effectively use PDG funds to support looked-after children with ALN by promoting leadership development, strategic use of PDG, and early intervention. Regional advisers can share good practices across regions, challenge individual schools on their use of PDG, and promote early intervention strategies to address learning needs proactively.&#10;&#10;4. Focus on social services and health: Beyond the PDG, local authorities should ensure that social services consider educational placement as part of their decision-making process when determining where a looked-after child will go to school. Similarly, health services must collaborate with education providers to address any underlying health issues that may impact a child's ability to learn.&#10;&#10;5. Ongoing evaluation and adaptation: Local authorities should regularly evaluate data on the educational outcomes of looked-after children and make adjustments to PDG eligibility criteria as needed. This flexible and responsive approach will help ensure that these children receive the support they need, regardless of their categorization within the school system.&#10;&#10;6. Increased awareness: Local authorities should work towards raising awareness about the availability and importance of PDG resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This will help promote more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and contribute to narrowing the attainment gap." />
    <node id=". We can't see the educational attainment of looked-after children just being a job of education. It's got to be a job of social services and the health service as well. There's got to be a joined-up approach to doing that. Now, officials were at the ministerial advisory group that's chaired by David Melding on prospects for looked-after children. They were there at the group last week. David tells me that the paper was very positively received by the group. I will be sitting down with David Melding to talk through what more we can do on the education side. I think there's really an appetite between me and the Minister for children to get a closer working relationship on this. We can't expect schools to do it on their own and alone. And there are things that we can do out there in local authorities to help improve outcomes. It's not just about the PDG; it is about, when social services are thinking about a placement, where does the discussion about where children are going to go to school—when does that take place? Do we talk about the placement, move a child and then think, 'Oh my goodness me, what are we going to do about the schooling?' If you can" />
    <node id="1. Tailored interventions for older children: Schools should create specific intervention strategies that cater to the unique needs and circumstances of older students, as one-size-fits-all approaches may not be as effective for this age group. For instance, a walking bus might not be suitable for 15 or 16-year-olds.&#10;&#10;2. Early intervention strategies: Addressing the root causes of poor attendance early on can prevent the problem from escalating. Schools can work with families to understand and overcome any barriers to regular school attendance.&#10;&#10;3. Working closely with families: Employing staff members to engage with the families of older children can help reinforce the link between attendance and attainment. These individuals can work individually with families to address barriers to attendance, gain a better understanding of the situation, and find ways for the school to tackle these issues more effectively.&#10;&#10;4. Flexible and responsive funding: Regular evaluations of data and adjustments to PDG eligibility criteria may be necessary to ensure that older children receive the support they need to improve their attendance and attainment. This includes looking into potential alternative ways to identify pupils in need and providing flexible and responsive funding to address their complex needs.&#10;&#10;Schools can work with families to address barriers to attendance by:&#10;1. Open communication: Maintaining open lines of communication with families, discussing any concerns, and involving them in the decision-making process regarding their child's education.&#10;2. Tailored support: Developing individualized support plans that consider the specific needs and circumstances of each family, such as flexible school schedules or remote learning options.&#10;3. Collaboration: Collaborating with other agencies, such as social services and health professionals, to address any underlying issues that may impact a child's ability to attend school regularly.&#10;4. Raising awareness: Increasing awareness about the importance of regular school attendance and the resources available through PDG to support looked-after children who may be at risk of poor attendance.&#10;5. Consistent monitoring and evaluation: Regularly evaluating attendance data, identifying trends, and adjusting strategies as needed to ensure that interventions are effective in improving attendance." />
    <edge source="1. The new schools categorization system in Wales uses improvement boards to identify and support schools based on their level of need, with &quot;red&quot; schools entitled to 25 days of support, more than was provided under the Schools Challenge Cymru program.&#10;2. This system allows for a more focused approach by targeting resources towards schools with greater needs, regardless of their type or sector, unlike the previous program that only supported secondary schools.&#10;3. By incorporating well-being into the national mission, the new system addresses various challenges faced by children within the school setting, ensuring they receive the necessary support to remain in school.&#10;4. The categorization system identifies schools based on their needs and provides intensive support to help them make improvements, with examples of Schools Challenge Cymru schools sustaining progress even after the program has ended.&#10;5. The Welsh Government is taking steps to improve the PDG agenda at a regional level by appointing new regional PDG advisers to ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, promoting good practice regionally." target=" feel free; this is your opportunity to do so if you—&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: What I would say is that those improvement boards are staying on, and our schools categorisation system is used to identify the level of support. Now, if you're a red school, that gives you the entitlement to 25 days of support. That is more than you would have got under the Schools Challenge Cymru programme, which would've been 20 days. So, actually, moving to this system allows us to really focus in on those schools that need that intensive level of support. And what's important for me, Llyr, in this, okay, is that those schools are not necessarily just the schools that were in the programme. Our system now of challenge, advice and support allows us to target resources