    <edge source="1. The new schools categorization system in Wales uses improvement boards to identify and support schools based on their level of need, with &quot;red&quot; schools entitled to 25 days of support, more than was provided under the Schools Challenge Cymru program.&#10;2. This system allows for a more focused approach by targeting resources towards schools with greater needs, regardless of their type or sector, unlike the previous program that only supported secondary schools.&#10;3. By incorporating well-being into the national mission, the new system addresses various challenges faced by children within the school setting, ensuring they receive the necessary support to remain in school.&#10;4. The categorization system identifies schools based on their needs and provides intensive support to help them make improvements, with examples of Schools Challenge Cymru schools sustaining progress even after the program has ended.&#10;5. The Welsh Government is taking steps to improve the PDG agenda at a regional level by appointing new regional PDG advisers to ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, promoting good practice regionally." target="1. Appointment of new PDG regional advisers: These advisers are tasked with spreading good practice regarding PDG usage across regions, ensuring strategic and consistent use of PDG in all schools. They will provide overall advice on the effective deployment of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;2. Strengthening the role of regional challenge advisers: Regional challenge advisers will work closely with individual schools to challenge their use of PDG. This includes examining how PDG is being targeted, the programs it is spent on, and whether there is an evidence base for its use and a clear impact on student learning.&#10;&#10;3. Promoting good practice regionally: Regional advisers will ensure that school challenge advisers are aware of best practices in using PDG, especially in targeting and spending decisions. They will encourage schools to adopt these strategies to maximize the effectiveness of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;4. Ensuring evidence-based use of PDG: Estyn recognizes that PDG is being used to support more able and talented students, but there is a need for strategic deployment across all schools. Regional advisers will work with schools to ensure that PDG usage is both strategic and evidence-based.&#10;&#10;5. Emphasizing leadership within individual schools: Effective use of PDG relies on strong leadership within schools. Regional advisers will encourage and support school leaders in making informed decisions about PDG spending, ensuring it is used appropriately and effectively to support student learning.&#10;&#10;6. Encouraging early intervention: To maximize the impact of PDG, regional advisers will emphasize the importance of early intervention strategies. This means using PDG funds earlier in a child's career, rather than just before exams, to provide support and address learning needs proactively.&#10;&#10;7. Monitoring and demonstrating proper use of PDG: Regional advisers will ensure that measures are in place to demonstrate that PDG is being used appropriately and consistently across schools. This will involve assessing the impact of PDG spending on student outcomes and making adjustments as needed.">
