    <edge source="1. Role of schools and regional consortia in providing PDG support for looked-after children: Schools are responsible for using PDG funds to provide support for looked-after children, while regional consortia play a role in improving the use of these funds through regionalization and collaboration. In 2015, it was decided that PDG for looked-after children would be regionalized, meaning regional consortia would have a more significant role in providing support to schools.&#10;2. Less awareness about PDG's availability for looked-after children: There is less awareness about PDG's availability for looked-after children because there are fewer looked-after children compared to those eligible for free school meals. Additionally, the focus has historically been on free school meals due to their higher numbers.&#10;&#10;The lower number of looked-after children and the regionalization of PDG support contribute to less awareness about its availability for this group. It is essential to improve communication and understanding of PDG's role in supporting looked-after children, so that schools and consortia can effectively use these funds to narrow the attainment gap for this vulnerable group." target="1. The growth mindset approach, implemented through the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG), has been shown to have a positive impact on the academic performance of free-school-meal children at the primary school level. This approach encourages learners to believe that they can improve their abilities and overcome failures, making them more resilient.&#10;2. Although this growth mindset training is provided universally to all students in a school, it has been observed to have a disproportionately positive effect on free-school-meal children. As a result, these children are now performing at the same level as their non-free-school-meal counterparts.&#10;3. This distinction is important because while individual interventions should be targeted specifically at children eligible for free school meals, whole-school approaches can also be effective in improving educational outcomes for this vulnerable group. By training all teachers and fostering a growth mindset ethos throughout the school, free-school-meal children benefit significantly.&#10;4. The key to successfully implementing the growth mindset approach through PDG funds is ensuring that schools use these resources effectively and demonstrate their impact on academic performance. Regional consortia play a crucial role in challenging and supporting schools in this process, promoting best practices and facilitating collaboration among educators.">
