issues that may lead to exclusion or non-attendance. By addressing these challenges proactively, local authorities can help prevent further deterioration in educational outcomes for these vulnerable children.&#10;&#10;3. Strategic use of PDG: Local authorities should ensure that schools effectively use PDG funds to support looked-after children with ALN by promoting leadership development, strategic use of PDG, and early intervention. Regional advisers can share good practices across regions, challenge individual schools on their use of PDG, and promote early intervention strategies to address learning needs proactively.&#10;&#10;4. Focus on social services and health: Beyond the PDG, local authorities should ensure that social services consider educational placement as part of their decision-making process when determining where a looked-after child will go to school. Similarly, health services must collaborate with education providers to address any underlying health issues that may impact a child's ability to learn.&#10;&#10;5. Ongoing evaluation and adaptation: Local authorities should regularly evaluate data on the educational outcomes of looked-after children and make adjustments to PDG eligibility criteria as needed. This flexible and responsive approach will help ensure that these children receive the support they need, regardless of their categorization within the school system.&#10;&#10;6. Increased awareness: Local authorities should work towards raising awareness about the availability and importance of PDG resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This will help promote more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and contribute to narrowing the attainment gap.">
