    <edge source=" improvement work. It's crucial.&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths AM&#10;Content: That sort of brings to mind some of the research that's been done on the role of the challenge advisers, Cabinet Secretary, which suggested that they're not actually challenging schools in that way, and that there's very little evidence of schools changing their decisions on the use of PDG as a result of any challenge from those challenge advisers. So, how would you respond to those findings?&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Well, as I said, in my scrutiny of the role and success of our regional consortia, I specifically asked them about free-school-meal performance and the use of PDG within their particular region. I think there is increasing evidence to suggest that good use is being made of that resource, and I think that is being fed back into us. Estyn tell us that it's one of the areas of school expenditure that is closely linked to research and an evidence base. But, clearly, there is more to do, and that's why we have appointed the new regional advisers for PDG going forward, because we think there can be improvements in how this agenda can be supported at a regional level.&#10;Speaker: John Griffiths" target="1. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers play a significant role in ensuring schools effectively use and demonstrate the impact of their PDG resources for school improvement work by scrutinizing how schools utilize these funds and asking probing questions about their strategies, impact, and outcomes. This helps maintain a focus on ensuring that PDG resources are used to their full potential and contribute to improved educational opportunities and outcomes for disadvantaged learners.&#10;2. By challenging and supporting schools in using PDG funds, regional consortia can help raise awareness of the availability and importance of these resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This approach promotes more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and helps narrow the attainment gap.&#10;3. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers are crucial in fostering a regional approach to good practice, as they can facilitate collaboration and knowledge-sharing among schools to identify successful strategies for utilizing PDG funds effectively. This helps create a culture of continuous improvement and ensures that best practices are disseminated and adopted more widely.&#10;4. To maximize the impact of regional consortia's challenge and support advisers in this area, it is essential to provide them with adequate training, resources, and guidance on PDG policies and best practices. Strengthening their role and capacities will enable them to contribute more effectively to school improvement efforts and help ensure that PDG funds are used in ways that lead to better outcomes for disadvantaged learners.">
