    <edge source="'m just wondering how comfortable you are that the money is being targeted appropriately because, clearly, it's being targeted more widely than just those eligible for free school meals, from some of the evidence we've had, but also that it seems to be predominantly focused on low-attaining frees—pupils who are eligible for free school meals.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: Thank you, Llyr. I think it's important to be absolutely clear that when it comes to individual interventions, those individual interventions should only be targeted at those children who are eligible for free school meals. But in some cases, schools may use their PDG funding to provide a universal intervention, but we would want to—in challenge advisers' discussions in schools—we'd want to have evidence that that universal intervention would have a disproportionate effect on the outcomes for children on free school meals. So, for instance, if I give you an example in your own region, Llyr: at Brynteg County Primary School in Wrexham, if you look at that primary school in Wrexham, their results for free-school-meal children at the end of their primary school period in school are equivalent to their non-free-school-meal counterparts." target="Based on the transcript, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, Kirsty Williams AM, acknowledges the concern about the apparent blurring of eligibility for the Pupil Development Grant (PDG) and its distribution beyond those eligible for free school meals. However, she also highlights that the PDG is being used appropriately in terms of providing strategic overall advice and challenging schools on their use of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;When asked if eligibility for free school meals is the best measure to identify which pupils to target, Kirsty Williams admits that it may not be perfect but is the best available proxy for need at present. She also mentions ongoing discussions with local government about potential alternative ways to identify pupils in need.&#10;&#10;Steve Davies adds that PDG funds are being used effectively in some secondary schools to employ resources like school nurses and counsellors, which benefit not just the children but their families as well. This demonstrates a wider use of PDG funds beyond simply targeting those eligible for free school meals.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, while there may be some discomfort with the apparent blurring of eligibility and wider distribution of PDG funds, the Cabinet Secretary for Education recognizes the importance of flexible and responsive funding to address the needs of pupils in Wales.">
