    <edge source="1. Strong, capable school leadership is crucial for driving change within the education system. This was a key lesson learned from the three-year investment in school leadership.&#10;2. Newly appointed headteachers can contribute significantly to the speed at which schools engage with improvement efforts, as seen in a significant minority of schools with recent appointments.&#10;3. The Government is applying these lessons by focusing on systems and processes, teacher quality, and collaborative activity in their wider school improvement program, the national mission.&#10;4. Expertise from the Schools Challenge Cymru program has been integrated into regional consortia to benefit all schools, not just a small proportion.&#10;5. The Government recognizes that there is always room for improvement and is strengthening the role of regional PDG advisers to ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, with a regional approach to good practice." target="1. Estyn, the education and training inspectorate for Wales, reported in 2015-2016 that regional consortia were not sufficiently focusing on particular groups of pupils, including vulnerable students, and tracking their outcomes.&#10;2. In response to this report, Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, stated that monitoring visits by Estyn in autumn 2017 found that three out of four regional consortia were making strong progress in their work, but that the Welsh Government was still working with one regional consortium to address the findings of the Estyn report.&#10;3. The newly appointed headteachers have been identified as contributing significantly to the speed at which schools engage with improvement efforts, as seen in a significant minority of schools with recent appointments. This is one of the lessons learned from the three-year investment in school leadership.&#10;4. The Government is focusing on systems and processes, teacher quality, and collaborative activity in their wider school improvement program, the national mission, to address this issue.&#10;5. Expertise from the Schools Challenge Cymru program has been integrated into regional consortia to benefit all schools, not just a small proportion.&#10;6. The Government recognizes that there is always room for improvement and is strengthening the role of regional PDG (Pupil Deprivation Grant) advisers to ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, with a regional approach to good practice.">
