    <edge source="1. Strong, capable school leadership is crucial for driving change within the education system. This was a key lesson learned from the three-year investment in school leadership.&#10;2. Newly appointed headteachers can contribute significantly to the speed at which schools engage with improvement efforts, as seen in a significant minority of schools with recent appointments.&#10;3. The Government is applying these lessons by focusing on systems and processes, teacher quality, and collaborative activity in their wider school improvement program, the national mission.&#10;4. Expertise from the Schools Challenge Cymru program has been integrated into regional consortia to benefit all schools, not just a small proportion.&#10;5. The Government recognizes that there is always room for improvement and is strengthening the role of regional PDG advisers to ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, with a regional approach to good practice." target="1. The recency of headteacher appointments and the effectiveness of support advisers played significant roles in the varying performance of schools in a program, as acknowledged by various speakers in the meeting transcript. Newly appointed headteachers were identified as contributing significantly to the speed at which schools engage with improvement efforts, as seen in a significant minority of schools with recent appointments. Additionally, the effectiveness of support advisers and challenge advisers varied, with some being &quot;really, really excellent and really good&quot; and driving change within individual schools, while others were less effective. The needs and challenges of individual schools also played a role in their performance, as some schools had more complex and deep-seated issues that required more intensive intervention.">
