    <edge source="Based on the transcript, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, Kirsty Williams AM, acknowledges the concern about the apparent blurring of eligibility for the Pupil Development Grant (PDG) and its distribution beyond those eligible for free school meals. However, she also highlights that the PDG is being used appropriately in terms of providing strategic overall advice and challenging schools on their use of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;When asked if eligibility for free school meals is the best measure to identify which pupils to target, Kirsty Williams admits that it may not be perfect but is the best available proxy for need at present. She also mentions ongoing discussions with local government about potential alternative ways to identify pupils in need.&#10;&#10;Steve Davies adds that PDG funds are being used effectively in some secondary schools to employ resources like school nurses and counsellors, which benefit not just the children but their families as well. This demonstrates a wider use of PDG funds beyond simply targeting those eligible for free school meals.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, while there may be some discomfort with the apparent blurring of eligibility and wider distribution of PDG funds, the Cabinet Secretary for Education recognizes the importance of flexible and responsive funding to address the needs of pupils in Wales." target="Based on the transcript, the lack of grade stability and resilience among children on free school meals is a complex issue that cannot be attributed solely to exam boards or the Welsh Qualifications Authority (WQA). Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, acknowledges that it could be one of the contributory factors but also mentions ongoing discussions with Qualifications Wales to better understand this. She has asked them to formally submit evidence ahead of her policy board meeting in May for a deeper investigation into this matter. It is clear that while exam boards and WQA are being considered as part of the problem, a broader examination of contributing factors and best practices is taking place.">
