    <edge source="Based on the transcript, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, Kirsty Williams AM, acknowledges the concern about the apparent blurring of eligibility for the Pupil Development Grant (PDG) and its distribution beyond those eligible for free school meals. However, she also highlights that the PDG is being used appropriately in terms of providing strategic overall advice and challenging schools on their use of PDG funds.&#10;&#10;When asked if eligibility for free school meals is the best measure to identify which pupils to target, Kirsty Williams admits that it may not be perfect but is the best available proxy for need at present. She also mentions ongoing discussions with local government about potential alternative ways to identify pupils in need.&#10;&#10;Steve Davies adds that PDG funds are being used effectively in some secondary schools to employ resources like school nurses and counsellors, which benefit not just the children but their families as well. This demonstrates a wider use of PDG funds beyond simply targeting those eligible for free school meals.&#10;&#10;In conclusion, while there may be some discomfort with the apparent blurring of eligibility and wider distribution of PDG funds, the Cabinet Secretary for Education recognizes the importance of flexible and responsive funding to address the needs of pupils in Wales." target="1. The growth mindset approach, implemented through the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG), has been shown to have a positive impact on the academic performance of free-school-meal children at the primary school level. This approach encourages learners to believe that they can improve their abilities and overcome failures, making them more resilient.&#10;2. Although this growth mindset training is provided universally to all students in a school, it has been observed to have a disproportionately positive effect on free-school-meal children. As a result, these children are now performing at the same level as their non-free-school-meal counterparts.&#10;3. This distinction is important because while individual interventions should be targeted specifically at children eligible for free school meals, whole-school approaches can also be effective in improving educational outcomes for this vulnerable group. By training all teachers and fostering a growth mindset ethos throughout the school, free-school-meal children benefit significantly.&#10;4. The key to successfully implementing the growth mindset approach through PDG funds is ensuring that schools use these resources effectively and demonstrate their impact on academic performance. Regional consortia play a crucial role in challenging and supporting schools in this process, promoting best practices and facilitating collaboration among educators.">
