    <edge source="1. Estyn, the education and training inspectorate for Wales, reported in 2015-2016 that regional consortia were not sufficiently focusing on particular groups of pupils, including vulnerable students, and tracking their outcomes.&#10;2. In response to this report, Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, stated that monitoring visits by Estyn in autumn 2017 found that three out of four regional consortia were making strong progress in their work, but that the Welsh Government was still working with one regional consortium to address the findings of the Estyn report.&#10;3. The newly appointed headteachers have been identified as contributing significantly to the speed at which schools engage with improvement efforts, as seen in a significant minority of schools with recent appointments. This is one of the lessons learned from the three-year investment in school leadership.&#10;4. The Government is focusing on systems and processes, teacher quality, and collaborative activity in their wider school improvement program, the national mission, to address this issue.&#10;5. Expertise from the Schools Challenge Cymru program has been integrated into regional consortia to benefit all schools, not just a small proportion.&#10;6. The Government recognizes that there is always room for improvement and is strengthening the role of regional PDG (Pupil Deprivation Grant) advisers to ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, with a regional approach to good practice." target="1. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers play a significant role in ensuring schools effectively use and demonstrate the impact of their PDG resources for school improvement work by scrutinizing how schools utilize these funds and asking probing questions about their strategies, impact, and outcomes. This helps maintain a focus on ensuring that PDG resources are used to their full potential and contribute to improved educational opportunities and outcomes for disadvantaged learners.&#10;2. By challenging and supporting schools in using PDG funds, regional consortia can help raise awareness of the availability and importance of these resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This approach promotes more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and helps narrow the attainment gap.&#10;3. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers are crucial in fostering a regional approach to good practice, as they can facilitate collaboration and knowledge-sharing among schools to identify successful strategies for utilizing PDG funds effectively. This helps create a culture of continuous improvement and ensures that best practices are disseminated and adopted more widely.&#10;4. To maximize the impact of regional consortia's challenge and support advisers in this area, it is essential to provide them with adequate training, resources, and guidance on PDG policies and best practices. Strengthening their role and capacities will enable them to contribute more effectively to school improvement efforts and help ensure that PDG funds are used in ways that lead to better outcomes for disadvantaged learners.">
