    <edge source="1. Estyn, the education and training inspectorate for Wales, reported in 2015-2016 that regional consortia were not sufficiently focusing on particular groups of pupils, including vulnerable students, and tracking their outcomes.&#10;2. In response to this report, Kirsty Williams AM, the Cabinet Secretary for Education, stated that monitoring visits by Estyn in autumn 2017 found that three out of four regional consortia were making strong progress in their work, but that the Welsh Government was still working with one regional consortium to address the findings of the Estyn report.&#10;3. The newly appointed headteachers have been identified as contributing significantly to the speed at which schools engage with improvement efforts, as seen in a significant minority of schools with recent appointments. This is one of the lessons learned from the three-year investment in school leadership.&#10;4. The Government is focusing on systems and processes, teacher quality, and collaborative activity in their wider school improvement program, the national mission, to address this issue.&#10;5. Expertise from the Schools Challenge Cymru program has been integrated into regional consortia to benefit all schools, not just a small proportion.&#10;6. The Government recognizes that there is always room for improvement and is strengthening the role of regional PDG (Pupil Deprivation Grant) advisers to ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, with a regional approach to good practice." target="1. Employing staff to work directly with families of older children: Schools like Ysgol y Preseli have employed staff specifically to engage with the families of older children, reinforcing the link between attendance and attainment. These staff members work individually with families to understand the barriers to attendance and find ways for the school to address those situations more effectively.&#10;&#10;2. Tailored interventions for older children: Recognizing that different approaches may be needed for older students, interventions should be tailored to their specific needs and circumstances. The example of a walking bus being less suitable for 15 or 16-year-olds illustrates this point.&#10;&#10;3. Early intervention strategies: By addressing the root causes of poor attendance early on, schools can prevent the problem from escalating. This can involve working with families to understand and overcome any barriers to regular school attendance.&#10;&#10;4. Strengthening regional PDG advisers' role: Newly appointed regional PDG advisers can play a crucial role in promoting best practices for improving school attendance, challenging individual schools on their use of PDG funds, and encouraging early intervention strategies. By ensuring that PDG is used strategically and consistently across all schools, these advisers can help narrow the attainment gap for vulnerable groups, including looked-after learners with ALN (Additional Learning Needs).&#10;&#10;5. Flexible and responsive funding: Regular evaluations of data and adjustments to PDG eligibility criteria may be necessary to ensure that older children, particularly those at key stage 4, receive the support they need to improve their attendance and attainment. This includes looking into potential alternative ways to identify pupils in need and providing flexible and responsive funding to address their complex needs.&#10;&#10;In summary, effective approaches for improving school attendance among older children include tailored interventions, early intervention strategies, and working closely with families to understand and address barriers to attendance. Strengthening the role of regional PDG advisers and ensuring flexible and responsive funding can also contribute significantly to addressing this issue.">
