    <edge source="1. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers play a significant role in ensuring schools effectively use and demonstrate the impact of their PDG resources for school improvement work by scrutinizing how schools utilize these funds and asking probing questions about their strategies, impact, and outcomes. This helps maintain a focus on ensuring that PDG resources are used to their full potential and contribute to improved educational opportunities and outcomes for disadvantaged learners.&#10;2. By challenging and supporting schools in using PDG funds, regional consortia can help raise awareness of the availability and importance of these resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This approach promotes more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and helps narrow the attainment gap.&#10;3. Regional consortia's challenge and support advisers are crucial in fostering a regional approach to good practice, as they can facilitate collaboration and knowledge-sharing among schools to identify successful strategies for utilizing PDG funds effectively. This helps create a culture of continuous improvement and ensures that best practices are disseminated and adopted more widely.&#10;4. To maximize the impact of regional consortia's challenge and support advisers in this area, it is essential to provide them with adequate training, resources, and guidance on PDG policies and best practices. Strengthening their role and capacities will enable them to contribute more effectively to school improvement efforts and help ensure that PDG funds are used in ways that lead to better outcomes for disadvantaged learners." target="1. Improved inter-agency collaboration: Strengthening the partnership between education, social services, and health is crucial for improving the educational attainment of looked-after children. This can be achieved by establishing a joined-up approach where all parties work together to address the complex needs of these children. Regular meetings and communication channels should be set up to discuss each child's progress and plan their support accordingly.&#10;&#10;2. Early intervention strategies: Local authorities can play a significant role in implementing early intervention strategies to identify and support looked-after children with additional learning needs (ALN) as soon as possible. This includes recognizing the connections between ALN and behavior issues that may lead to exclusion or non-attendance. By addressing these challenges proactively, local authorities can help prevent further deterioration in educational outcomes for these vulnerable children.&#10;&#10;3. Strategic use of PDG: Local authorities should ensure that schools effectively use PDG funds to support looked-after children with ALN by promoting leadership development, strategic use of PDG, and early intervention. Regional advisers can share good practices across regions, challenge individual schools on their use of PDG, and promote early intervention strategies to address learning needs proactively.&#10;&#10;4. Focus on social services and health: Beyond the PDG, local authorities should ensure that social services consider educational placement as part of their decision-making process when determining where a looked-after child will go to school. Similarly, health services must collaborate with education providers to address any underlying health issues that may impact a child's ability to learn.&#10;&#10;5. Ongoing evaluation and adaptation: Local authorities should regularly evaluate data on the educational outcomes of looked-after children and make adjustments to PDG eligibility criteria as needed. This flexible and responsive approach will help ensure that these children receive the support they need, regardless of their categorization within the school system.&#10;&#10;6. Increased awareness: Local authorities should work towards raising awareness about the availability and importance of PDG resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This will help promote more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and contribute to narrowing the attainment gap.">
