    <edge source="Based on the meeting transcript, Cabinet Secretary Kirsty Williams does not seem to be opposed to having further conversations about the lessons learned from the Schools Challenge Cymru program if there is advice indicating that they have not sufficiently learned those lessons. However, she expresses confidence that they have already learned the lessons and are applying them to the wider school improvement agenda. She mentions that there has been ongoing dialogue with a variety of people involved in the program and that they are actively considering developing a Welsh toolkit around good practice, evidence base, and research. Therefore, while she is open to further conversations, her stance suggests that she believes that they have already effectively learned and applied the lessons from the Schools Challenge Cymru program." target="1. The new schools categorization system in Wales provides a more targeted and intensive level of support for identified schools by using improvement boards to identify schools based on their level of need, with &quot;red&quot; schools entitled to 25 days of support. This is an increase from the 20 days of support provided under the Schools Challenge Cymru program. The new system targets resources towards schools with greater needs, regardless of their type or sector, which was not the case with the previous program that only supported secondary schools.&#10;2. This new system also addresses various challenges faced by children within the school setting, ensuring they receive the necessary support to remain in school. By incorporating well-being into the national mission, it ensures that schools identified as needing improvement will receive the required intensive support to help them make improvements. Examples of Schools Challenge Cymru schools have sustained progress even after the program has ended, indicating the potential for success with this new system.&#10;3. The Welsh Government is taking steps to improve the PDG (Pupil Development Grant) agenda at a regional level by appointing new regional PDG advisers. This will ensure individual school challenge advisers know what they should be looking for and doing, promoting good practice regionally. This further strengthens the support provided to schools in need of improvement under the new system.">
