    <edge source="1. The evolution of using the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG) in Welsh schools has not been significantly driven by cuts to core funding but rather by an increased focus on the agenda, improved understanding, and a better utilization of growing research and evidence.&#10;2. PDG funds have played a crucial role in concentrating the minds of school leadership and senior management teams, highlighting the importance of this agenda within schools and raising it in their thinking.&#10;3. As schools embark on a journey from a low base where this was not a priority for them, they are increasingly learning to use evidence and research from both Wales and outside sources to tailor approaches in their schools. This reflects the changing use of PDG funds.&#10;4. Regional consortia collaborate with schools to improve the use of PDG funds for looked-after children, although there is less awareness about PDG's availability due to fewer numbers and a historical focus on free school meals. Increased communication and understanding of PDG's role in supporting this vulnerable group are essential.&#10;5. The new schools categorization system targets resources towards schools with greater needs, regardless of their type or sector, incorporating well-being into the national mission and addressing various challenges faced by children within the school setting.&#10;6. Effective use of PDG funds includes leadership development, strategic usage, early intervention, and proper monitoring to ensure good practice is shared across regions and that PDG funds are not used to cover other funding gaps." target=" You mentioned some schools will be moving from the tried-and-tested interventions, really, and I'm just wondering to what extent that evolution of use of PDG is being driven by cuts to core funding.&#10;Speaker: Kirsty Williams AM&#10;Content: No, I don't think it's being driven by cuts to core funding. I think there has been—. One of the biggest impacts of PDG has not been—well, I suppose it is the money in itself, because the money has concentrated the minds, hasn't it? So, one of the most important things that PDG has done is highlight the importance of this agenda within schools, and really raise this up in the thinking of leadership and senior management teams in our schools, and has driven a focus on scrutiny and accountability in the systems that are working with our schools. I think the changing use of PDG reflects the journeys that schools have been on, some of them from a very low base where this was not a priority for them, to better understanding, and as research and as intelligence grows over time in this area, both in Wales and outside of Wales, schools are increasingly learning to use that evidence to tailor approaches in their schools.&#10;Speaker: Llyr Gruffy">
