    <edge source="1. The evolution of using the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG) in Welsh schools has not been significantly driven by cuts to core funding but rather by an increased focus on the agenda, improved understanding, and a better utilization of growing research and evidence.&#10;2. PDG funds have played a crucial role in concentrating the minds of school leadership and senior management teams, highlighting the importance of this agenda within schools and raising it in their thinking.&#10;3. As schools embark on a journey from a low base where this was not a priority for them, they are increasingly learning to use evidence and research from both Wales and outside sources to tailor approaches in their schools. This reflects the changing use of PDG funds.&#10;4. Regional consortia collaborate with schools to improve the use of PDG funds for looked-after children, although there is less awareness about PDG's availability due to fewer numbers and a historical focus on free school meals. Increased communication and understanding of PDG's role in supporting this vulnerable group are essential.&#10;5. The new schools categorization system targets resources towards schools with greater needs, regardless of their type or sector, incorporating well-being into the national mission and addressing various challenges faced by children within the school setting.&#10;6. Effective use of PDG funds includes leadership development, strategic usage, early intervention, and proper monitoring to ensure good practice is shared across regions and that PDG funds are not used to cover other funding gaps." target="1. The growth mindset approach, implemented through the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG), has been shown to have a positive impact on the academic performance of free-school-meal children at the primary school level. This approach encourages learners to believe that they can improve their abilities and overcome failures, making them more resilient.&#10;2. Although this growth mindset training is provided universally to all students in a school, it has been observed to have a disproportionately positive effect on free-school-meal children. As a result, these children are now performing at the same level as their non-free-school-meal counterparts.&#10;3. This distinction is important because while individual interventions should be targeted specifically at children eligible for free school meals, whole-school approaches can also be effective in improving educational outcomes for this vulnerable group. By training all teachers and fostering a growth mindset ethos throughout the school, free-school-meal children benefit significantly.&#10;4. The key to successfully implementing the growth mindset approach through PDG funds is ensuring that schools use these resources effectively and demonstrate their impact on academic performance. Regional consortia play a crucial role in challenging and supporting schools in this process, promoting best practices and facilitating collaboration among educators.">
