    <edge source="1. The growth mindset approach, implemented through the Pupil Deprivation Grant (PDG), has been shown to have a positive impact on the academic performance of free-school-meal children at the primary school level. This approach encourages learners to believe that they can improve their abilities and overcome failures, making them more resilient.&#10;2. Although this growth mindset training is provided universally to all students in a school, it has been observed to have a disproportionately positive effect on free-school-meal children. As a result, these children are now performing at the same level as their non-free-school-meal counterparts.&#10;3. This distinction is important because while individual interventions should be targeted specifically at children eligible for free school meals, whole-school approaches can also be effective in improving educational outcomes for this vulnerable group. By training all teachers and fostering a growth mindset ethos throughout the school, free-school-meal children benefit significantly.&#10;4. The key to successfully implementing the growth mindset approach through PDG funds is ensuring that schools use these resources effectively and demonstrate their impact on academic performance. Regional consortia play a crucial role in challenging and supporting schools in this process, promoting best practices and facilitating collaboration among educators." target=" their results for free-school-meal children at the end of their primary school period in school are equivalent to their non-free-school-meal counterparts. So, there is no differentiation in those results. One of the things that they've used their PDG for is to really focus on the concept of growth mindset in school. So, that's a universal thing that they've trained all the teachers in, but what we know is that that has a disproportionate effect on those children who are on free school meals. So, if you're familiar with the concept of a growth mindset, it's about really challenging learners to think that, 'I can do things. If sometimes I fail, I pick myself up, I'm more resilient.' Now, that has been, as I said, trained to all the teachers in the school—it's an ethos for the whole school—but we have seen that the impact on the free-school-meal children has been even greater, and now they're at the same level. So, that's the important distinction. Individual intervention per child has to be targeted at those children who are eligible for free school meals, but sometimes a school will employ a whole-school approach to train their staff, for instance, and that,">
