    <edge source="1. Improved inter-agency collaboration: Strengthening the partnership between education, social services, and health is crucial for improving the educational attainment of looked-after children. This can be achieved by establishing a joined-up approach where all parties work together to address the complex needs of these children. Regular meetings and communication channels should be set up to discuss each child's progress and plan their support accordingly.&#10;&#10;2. Early intervention strategies: Local authorities can play a significant role in implementing early intervention strategies to identify and support looked-after children with additional learning needs (ALN) as soon as possible. This includes recognizing the connections between ALN and behavior issues that may lead to exclusion or non-attendance. By addressing these challenges proactively, local authorities can help prevent further deterioration in educational outcomes for these vulnerable children.&#10;&#10;3. Strategic use of PDG: Local authorities should ensure that schools effectively use PDG funds to support looked-after children with ALN by promoting leadership development, strategic use of PDG, and early intervention. Regional advisers can share good practices across regions, challenge individual schools on their use of PDG, and promote early intervention strategies to address learning needs proactively.&#10;&#10;4. Focus on social services and health: Beyond the PDG, local authorities should ensure that social services consider educational placement as part of their decision-making process when determining where a looked-after child will go to school. Similarly, health services must collaborate with education providers to address any underlying health issues that may impact a child's ability to learn.&#10;&#10;5. Ongoing evaluation and adaptation: Local authorities should regularly evaluate data on the educational outcomes of looked-after children and make adjustments to PDG eligibility criteria as needed. This flexible and responsive approach will help ensure that these children receive the support they need, regardless of their categorization within the school system.&#10;&#10;6. Increased awareness: Local authorities should work towards raising awareness about the availability and importance of PDG resources for looked-after children, who may not receive as much attention due to their smaller numbers compared to those eligible for free school meals. This will help promote more equitable distribution of resources and support across different vulnerable groups and contribute to narrowing the attainment gap." target=". We can't see the educational attainment of looked-after children just being a job of education. It's got to be a job of social services and the health service as well. There's got to be a joined-up approach to doing that. Now, officials were at the ministerial advisory group that's chaired by David Melding on prospects for looked-after children. They were there at the group last week. David tells me that the paper was very positively received by the group. I will be sitting down with David Melding to talk through what more we can do on the education side. I think there's really an appetite between me and the Minister for children to get a closer working relationship on this. We can't expect schools to do it on their own and alone. And there are things that we can do out there in local authorities to help improve outcomes. It's not just about the PDG; it is about, when social services are thinking about a placement, where does the discussion about where children are going to go to school—when does that take place? Do we talk about the placement, move a child and then think, 'Oh my goodness me, what are we going to do about the schooling?' If you can">
      <data key="d0">1</data>
    </edge>
